<ArticleLayout
  title="Baby Monitors for Australian Homes"
  description="Compare audio and video baby monitors, with or without Wi-Fi, including range, battery life, privacy and night vision."
  category="Nursery & Kids"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="8 minute read"
  image="/images/Nursery-kids.webp"
  imageAlt="A tidy nursery room with timber furniture, soft lighting and practical baby storage"
>
  <p>
    A monitor may be reassuring when the baby sleeps on another floor or at the far end of the
    house. In a compact home, you may hear everything without one. The layout of the home is a
    better starting point than the length of the feature list.
  </p>
  <p>
    The main choice is between sound, video and an internet connection. Range, battery life,
    privacy and where the monitor can sit then narrow the options.
  </p>

  <h2>The main choices at a glance</h2>
  <ComparisonTable rows={comparisonRows} caption="Baby monitor type comparison" />

  <h2>What a monitor can and cannot do</h2>
  <p>
    A baby monitor is a device that helps parents or carers hear, see or receive alerts from a
    baby's sleep space or room. Some are audio-only, some include video, and some connect
    through Wi-Fi or an app.
  </p>

  <h2>When sound may be enough</h2>
  <p>
    Audio-only monitors are a simple option. They are usually less expensive and may suit
    smaller homes or parents who only want sound alerts rather than a video feed. Check sound
    clarity, range, battery life and volume controls before deciding whether one is enough.
  </p>

  <h2>When video may help</h2>
  <p>
    Video monitors are useful for visual checks. They may help parents see whether a baby is
    awake, settled or moving without entering the room. Compare screen size, night vision,
    camera angle, battery life, range and whether extra cameras are supported if you may use
    the monitor across more than one room.
  </p>

  <h2>Monitors that use Wi-Fi</h2>
  <p>
    Wi-Fi baby monitors connect through home internet and usually an app. They can be useful
    when parents want remote viewing or access from a phone. Check app requirements, privacy
    settings, account security, update support, internet reliability and whether the device
    still works during outages.
  </p>

  <h2>Monitors with their own parent unit</h2>
  <p>
    Non-Wi-Fi monitors usually connect directly between a camera and a parent unit. They may
    suit parents who prefer not to use an app. Check range, signal reliability, screen quality
    and whether walls or other devices may cause interference.
  </p>

  <h2>Features worth comparing</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li><strong>Range:</strong> check the distance between the baby's room and the areas where adults spend time.</li>
    <li><strong>Battery life:</strong> compare parent-unit battery life, charging time and low-battery alerts.</li>
    <li><strong>Night vision:</strong> check image clarity in low light and whether the picture is easy to understand.</li>
    <li><strong>Two-way audio:</strong> useful for some families, unnecessary for others.</li>
    <li><strong>Temperature display:</strong> helpful as a room reference, but not a substitute for safe sleep guidance.</li>
    <li><strong>Multiple camera support:</strong> useful for more than one child or room.</li>
    <li><strong>Wall mounting or stand options:</strong> check safe placement and follow manufacturer instructions.</li>
    <li><strong>App access:</strong> compare account setup, notifications and who can access the feed.</li>
    <li><strong>Privacy and security settings:</strong> check passwords, updates, encryption information and app permissions.</li>
    <li><strong>Warranty and support:</strong> look for clear support information and current product details.</li>
    <li><strong>Replacement parts or chargers:</strong> check whether parts are easy to identify and replace.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Checks that may change your choice</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Room size and distance from the parent area.</li>
    <li>Whether walls, floors or outdoor spaces may affect signal.</li>
    <li>Whether you want Wi-Fi or app access.</li>
    <li>Whether the monitor works without internet.</li>
    <li>Battery life for the parent unit or portable screen.</li>
    <li>Camera placement and cable safety near the baby's sleep space.</li>
    <li>Mounting options and whether they suit your room.</li>
    <li>Warranty, return policy and support availability.</li>
    <li>Current product information, manufacturer instructions and privacy information.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Where monitor choices go wrong</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Choosing based only on screen size.</li>
    <li>Ignoring Wi-Fi and privacy settings.</li>
    <li>Forgetting to check battery life.</li>
    <li>Placing cords too close to the baby's sleep space.</li>
    <li>Assuming expensive means better.</li>
    <li>Choosing more features than needed.</li>
    <li>Not checking whether the app requires a subscription.</li>
    <li>Not checking whether spare chargers or replacement parts are available.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Decide from the room outwards</h2>
  <p>
    For many Australian homes, a simple video monitor or audio monitor may be enough. Larger
    homes, two-storey homes or households that want app access may prefer different features.
    The best choice depends on room layout, comfort level, privacy preferences and budget.
  </p>

  <RelatedGuidesBlock guides={relatedGuides} />
  <FAQBlock items={faqs} />
</ArticleLayout>
